<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4432&amp;p=38123#p38123</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4432&amp;p=38123#p38123"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Is the first note of the scale A or C ?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4432&amp;p=38123#p38123"><![CDATA[
Here's the formula I use:<br />F = B * 2^((N-N0)/12)<br /><br />Where B is some arbitrary base frequency<br />N is your note number (in half steps, 12 notes to an octave)<br />N0 is the note number of frequency B<br /><br />B=440 and N0=57 by the definition of note A4.<br /><br />Note numbers:<br />Examples of notes include C4, D2, A#3, etc.  It's a note name, optional sharp or flat, and octave number.<br />Named notes are numbered like this:<br />C=0<br />D=2<br />E=4<br />F=5<br />G=7<br />A=9<br />B=11<br />For sharp, add 1.  For flat subtract 1.<br /><br />C4 = 12*4 + 0 = #48<br />D2 = 12*2 + 2 = #26<br />F#3 = 12*3 + 9 + 1 = #42<br />A4 = 12*4 + 9 = #57<br />A4 is defined to have a frequency of 440Hz.<br /><br />Middle C is C4, and it has a frequency of<br />=440 * 2^((48-57)/12)<br />=440 * 2^(-9/12)<br />=261.625...<br /><br />I have no clue where your formula came from.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=53">Dwedit</a> — Mon Oct 06, 2008 6:52 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
