<title type="html"><![CDATA[Is the first note of the scale A or C ?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4432&amp;p=38105#p38105"><![CDATA[
In not math-related music, it seems that C is a reference note. All white keys on a piano can be played starting at C to one octave above that C to play the C major scale. Though I believe that A is the mathematical start of an octave, as it's 440 KHz exactly and almost every audible tone of A is a whole number of KHz, and like you said, it's the letter A, which is the first letter of the alphabet. Pretty much everything after A isn't a whole number of KHz, so I have that reason to believe that A is the real start of an octave.<br /><br />EDIT: Also, the piano starts with an A as the bottom key. Just thought I'd mention that.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=138">Celius</a> — Sun Oct 05, 2008 7:20 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
